The problem with your current approach is that you&#39;re advancing which element you&#39;re looking at too soon. At the first occurrence of a match, you should be comparing the original first item, to the next after. You&#39;re only looking at adjacent items.

You can craft an xpath query that could select `&lt;Update&gt;` elements that have the same id and rotation as the previous pretty easily.

    //Update[preceding-sibling::Update/Properties/@id      =Properties/@id
         and preceding-sibling::Update/Properties/@rotation=Properties/@rotation]

Then alter these elements as needed.

    var xpath = &quot;//Update[preceding-sibling::Update/Properties/@id=Properties/@id and preceding-sibling::Update/Properties/@rotation=Properties/@rotation]&quot;;
    var fixUpdates = doc.XPathSelectElements(xpath);
    var fixProperties = fixUpdates.Elements(&quot;Properties&quot;);
    var removeMe = fixProperties.Attributes(&quot;rotation&quot;);
    removeMe.Remove();

